  "sections": {
    "Background": {
      "text": "Associated with penetrating or blunt trauma to lower\nchest\n/\nupper abdomen\n~65% from penetrating, 35% from blunt\n[1]\nIf missed, can lead to herniation of viscera and tension enterothorax\nMost commonly left sided\nMajority will have other injuries which can mask symptoms of diaphragm injury\n75% of the time occurs on the left side; the liver is protective on the right side\nPresentation can be delayed months to years after the initial trauma",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
      "links": [
        {
          "text": "chest",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Thoracic_trauma"
        },
        {
          "text": "upper abdomen",
          "url": "https://wikem.org/wiki/Abdominal_trauma"
        }
      ]
    },
    "Clinical_Features": {
      "text": "Upper abdominal\n/\nlower chest pain\nShortness of breath\nDiminished breath sounds on side of rupture\nKehr Sign: shoulder pain from referred diaphragm pain",
      "subsections": {},
      "tables": [],
